ations of the Western legal tradition under the impact of the sixteenth-century German Reformation and the seventeenth-century English Revolution, with particular emphasis on Lutheran and Calvinist influences. Berman examines the far-reaching consequences of these apocalyptic political and social upheavals on the systems of legal philosophy, legal science, criminal law, civil and economic law, and social law in Germany and England and throughout Europe as a whole. Berman challenges both conventional approaches to legal history, which have neglected the religious foundations of Western legal systems, and standard social theory, which has paid insufficient attention to the communitarian dimensions of early modern economic law, including corporation law and social welfare. Clearly written and cogently argued, this long-awaited, magisterial work is a major contribution to an understanding of the relationship of law to Western belief systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristianity and lawxHistory. 0aLawzEuropexHistory. 0aReformationxInfluence. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067402086340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674020863423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674020863.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyt